@rem *******************************************************************
@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@rem *******************************************************************
@next "Installation"
@prev "Copyright"

@{JLEFT}This programm is a two-in-one programm: Called from CLI it can
display some important dates in your life, like the @{i}1000000000th second of
your life@{ui}.  Called from workbench it is a freely configurable seconds
countup/down for any date A.D..

The date calculation routines can handle the range since 1. January 1 till
the very far future (some million years). The limiting factor is the
amigados clock value that wraps after 2^32 seconds (136 Years). Because the
amigados date starts 1-Jan-1980 this will be in the year 2116 (Perhaps you
will have a super-cray-amiga-emulator at this time ;-)). This limitation
applies only to the actual system time not to the dates you enter as birthday.

@endnode

@rem *******************************************************************
@node "Installation" "Installation"
@rem *******************************************************************
@next "ToolTypes"
@prev "Introduction"
@{JLEFT}The installation of SecAge is quiet easy. Just copy the folder to where
you want the program to reside. Usually you might want it to be started at
boot time. Then move the program to the WBStartup folder. The icon tooltypes
are suitable for this.

If you like to install the program in your WBStartup folder
@{fg fill}now@{fg text} press the Install button below (older versions will be overwritten!).


@{JCENTER}
@{"Install to WBStartup" SYSTEM "copy SecAge SecAge.info TO SYS:WBStartup/ CLONE"}


@{JLEFT}After installations adjust the tooltypes.
@endnode

@rem *******************************************************************
@node "ToolTypes" "Workbench Usage"
@rem *******************************************************************
@next "CLIUsage"
@prev "Installation"
When called from the workbench the program displays a digital clock with
the seconds since/to the date given by the tooltypes. The following
tooltypes are accepted:

@{b}BIRTHDATE@{ub} = DD-MM-YYYY

@{b}BIRTHTIME@{ub} = HH:MM:SS

@{b}WINDOWX@{ub}   = X-Offset of the window

@{b}WINDOWY@{ub}   = Y-Offset of the window

@{b}FORMAT@{ub}    = A format string for the output containing %d for the number of
seconds.

@{b}ADDWIDTH@{ub}  = Number of pixels to add to the window width. This might be
usefull if the size of the close gadget will change one day, because there
is no clean way to determine it.

@endnode

@rem *******************************************************************
@node "CLIUsage" "CLI-Usage"
@rem *******************************************************************
@next "History"
@prev "ToolTypes"
When called from the CLI it takes only two arguments:


  @{b}SecAge BIRTHDATE/A,BIRTHTIME@{ub}


BIRTHDATE is your birthdate in the format @{b}DD-MM-YYYY@{ub}.

BIRTHTIME is the time of your birth in the format @{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub}. If
no time is given, it defaults to 00:00:00.


The format for date and time is quiet flexible. You can use
any of ":-.,;/" as separator characters.


Click @{"here" SYSTEM "secage >CON:///200/Secage-by-Georg-Wiora/AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE 29-11-1967 10:30"} for a
demo with my birthdate. The call sequence is:


  @{b}secage 29-11-1967 10:30@{ub}

@endnode

@rem *******************************************************************
@node "History" "History"
@rem *******************************************************************
@prev "CLIUsage"
@next "Examples"
@{code}
revision 2.3
date: 1998/06/07 02:58:14;  author: Wiora;  state: Rel;  lines: +45 -27
Added support for AmigaDos getclk() function, because the unix
uptime(time()) wrappes after 1970+2^31 seconds. The amigados
function wrappes after 1980+2^32 seconds (2116). If amigados
functions are not availible (_AMIGA not defined) the unix functions
are used instead..
----------------------------
revision 2.2
date: 1998/06/06 21:05:26;  author: Wiora;  state: Stab;  lines: +190 -53
The window is now font sensitive and uses the screens default font.
The width of the window is automaticly adjusted to the string width.
The output string is now configurable.
The width can be increased by a tooltype because the size of the system
gadgeds might change one day and there is no clean way to determine this.
----------------------------
revision 2.1
date: 1998/06/02 00:20:24;  author: Wiora;  state: Exp;  lines: +202 -54
Workbench window and ToolTypes added. CLI-Call and Workbench Call work
different!.
----------------------------
